Delicious food - we had the lagman soup, fried lagman and liver. Speaking Russian or Uzbek may be necessary in order for you to order your food. Around 1pm most of the menu wasn’t available so I’d suggest this establishment more for dinner than for lunch.  One tasteless and tacky decorative piece was the big picture of Trump and the Uzbek President at the front of the restaurant - almost like a tribute from serfs to their god king. Perhaps some Uzbek or central asian decorative pieces would be a more apt tribute to ones culture than an almost religious tribute to politicians.
Hearty and tasty food, great experience and service. Fancy and authentic decor. Loved it, especially the Kazan Kabeb and Lagman soup. The only downside was limited availability of some menu items.

Had a dinner while traveling in NYC in January, 2020. Best experience ever among Uzbek restaurants in the US. Remembered my city, Tashkent. I give 10 out of 10 for Tashkent plov, which is made and taste the same way as it does at "Plov Center" in Tashkent. Bread made in tandoori, "Lepeshki", reminded me my mom who used to ask me to go to buy "Lepeshki" early in the morning. Kebabs are very juicy and tasty, like Uzbeks love it. They tried really hard to give their guests home atmosphere. Unfortunately, they were out of "somsa" (samosa). They sold them out earlier, and we came late around 7 pm. But I've read a lot of positive reviews about their somsa made in tandoori. Anyways, we'll come back to try somsa next time. Thank you!
